sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM player_game_stats 
WHERE player_id = 1;

SELECT player_id, SUM(points) AS total_points
FROM player_game_stats
GROUP BY player_id;

external_knowledge:
The "past year" in the question refers to the period from January 1, 2022, to December 31, 2022;
Average points are calculated by dividing the total points by the number of games played;
The higher the average points, the better the performance in terms of scoring.

sql:
SELECT p.name
FROM players p
JOIN (
    SELECT player_id, AVG(points) AS avg_points
    FROM player_game_stats
    GROUP BY player_id
    HAVING AVG(points) > (
        SELECT AVG(points) FROM player_game_stats
    )
) pg ON p.player_id = pg.player_id;

external_knowledge:
- "shining stars" refers to prominent players who stand out due to their high scores; 
- "illuminated the game's leaderboard" metaphorically describes their performance in terms of points scored, where high scorers are considered to be the brightest and most visible on the leaderboard;
- "top five scorers" refers to players ranked 1st to 5th based on the total points scored.

- "Wasteful handling" refers to turnovers;
- "Best scoring game" refers to the maximum points scored in any game;
- "Average passing efficiency" is determined by the average number of assists;
- "Total grab power" indicates the overall number of rebounds made;
- "Games they participated in" counts the total number of games each player played.
